Extra Important Concepts:
1. What Are Pins and Pin Wiggles?
â¤ Pins: Pins are the input/output signals of a module (DUT â€” Device Under Test). Each pin carries a logical 0 or 1.

Example:
module simple_adder (
  input  logic clk,
  input  logic [3:0] a,
  input  logic [3:0] b,
  output logic [4:0] sum
);
Here, a, b, and clk are input pins; sum is an output pin.

â¤ Pin Wiggles: â€œPin wigglesâ€ means how those signals change over time â€” their transitions from 0 â†’ 1 â†’ 0 as per the protocol rules.
In other words, when we say "the driver wiggles pins," it means the driver drives the DUT inputs in a particular pattern to simulate transactions.

Example: To perform a write, the driver sets:
valid = 1 (asserted)
addr = 0x10
data = 0xAB
waits until ready = 1
then sets valid = 0 (deasserted)

Each of those changes is a pin wiggle.


-------------------------

âš™ï¸ 2. What Are VALID, READY, and HANDSHAKE?

These signals are used to synchronize data transfer between two blocks â€” the sender and the receiver.
â¤ Meaning:
Signal	                                 Controlled By	                          Meaning
valid	                                       Sender	                     "I have data ready to send."
ready	                                      Receiver	                    "Iâ€™m ready to accept data."
Handshake	                                    Both	                   When both are 1 together â€” data is transferred!

â¤ Real-world Analogy:
Imagine passing a book to a friend:
You lift your hand (valid = 1): â€œIâ€™m ready to give.â€
Your friend lifts theirs (ready = 1): â€œI can take it.â€
When both hands are up (valid & ready = 1): handshake â†’ the book is passed.

â¤ Handshake Table
Cycle	       valid         	ready	          What Happens
t0	           0	            0	               Idle
t1	           1	            0	              Sender has data, waiting
t2	           1	            1	             âœ… Handshake â†’ transfer done
t3	           0	            1	               Sender done, deasserts valid

â¤ Visual:
clk:   _|â€¾|_|â€¾|_|â€¾|_|â€¾|_
valid: ___â€¾â€¾â€¾â€¾â€¾â€¾__________
ready: _______â€¾â€¾â€¾â€¾_______
data : ___[ D1 ]_________

Data D1 is accepted when valid & ready overlap.

-------------------------

ğŸ§  3. Assert vs Deassert
In digital design, every signal can be activated (asserted) or deactivated (deasserted).

Action	                             Meaning	                                           Example
Assert valid	                      Set valid = 1 â†’ "I have data."	                 Sender activates it
Deassert valid	                    Set valid = 0 â†’ "Iâ€™m done sending."	             Sender turns it off
Assert ready	                      Set ready = 1 â†’ "I can accept data."	           Receiver activates it
Deassert ready	                    Set ready = 0 â†’ "Iâ€™m busy."	                     Receiver turns it off

ğŸ§© Tip: â€œAssertâ€ means drive a signal to its active state, which could be high (1) or low (0) depending on design (e.g., reset_n is active low â†’ assert = 0).

-------------------------

âš¡ 4. What are â€œbus protocolsâ€ in simple terms?
Think of a bus protocol as a rulebook for communication between different parts of a chip.
In a chip (like an SoC), there are many blocks:
CPU
Memory
Peripherals (UART, SPI, I2C, GPIO, etc.)
Accelerators (AI, GPU, etc.)

All these need to send and receive data between each other. They donâ€™t connect randomly â€” they follow a standard communication system called a bus.
So a bus protocol defines:
ğŸ‘‰ How data is transferred, how to start and end a transfer, how to signal readiness, and how to avoid conflicts.

***What Are AXI, AHB, and APB?
These are defined by ARM, a company that makes processor architectures and also standard interconnect protocols. They define how different blocks (CPU, memory, peripherals) exchange data.

Protocol	         Full Name	                             Use Case	                                 Complexity
APB	           Advanced Peripheral Bus	            Low-speed devices (GPIO, UART, timers)	           Simple
AHB	           Advanced High-performance Bus	           CPU â†” Memory	                                 Medium
AXI	           Advanced eXtensible Interface	          SoC-level interconnects	                     Complex / Fast


***Why do we need different buses?
Different parts of a chip have different needs:
Some need speed (CPU â†” DDR memory)
Some need simplicity and low power (GPIO)
Some need burst or pipelined transfers

Thatâ€™s why ARM created a family of buses â€” each for a level of complexity.


*** Quick overview of each one
ğŸ”¹ APB (Advanced Peripheral Bus)
Simplest of the three.
Used for low-speed peripherals like UART, GPIO, timers.
No pipelining â†’ one transfer at a time.
Signals are like: PADDR, PWDATA, PRDATA, PWRITE, PENABLE, PSEL.
Easy to understand and verify â€” perfect for beginners.
Think of APB as â€œslow, steady communicationâ€ â€” like a one-way walkie-talkie conversation.

ğŸ”¹ AHB (Advanced High-performance Bus)
Faster than APB.
Used between processor, memory, and high-speed peripherals.
Supports burst transfers (multiple data words back-to-back).
Slightly more complex control signals.
Typical signals: HADDR, HWRITE, HREADY, HRESP, HWDATA, HRDATA.
Think of AHB as a highway â€” several data words can move in sequence, still fairly simple.

ğŸ”¹ AXI (Advanced eXtensible Interface)
The most advanced and fastest.
Used in modern SoCs (CPUs, GPUs, DMA, memory).
Fully pipelined: multiple transactions can be â€œin flight.â€
Separate channels for read/write â†’ more parallelism.
Uses VALID/READY handshake on every channel.

â¤ Why DV Engineers Learn Them
Real SoCs use these buses for most communication.
Youâ€™ll write drivers, monitors, and checkers for these interfaces.
Industry-standard VIPs (Verification IPs) use AXI/AHB/APB protocols.

---------------------------

ğŸ¥ 5. What Is a Monitor in UVM?
A monitor is a passive observer in the UVM testbench. It watches DUT signals and reports what happens â€” but never drives anything.

â¤ Monitorâ€™s Job
Watch DUT interface signals (e.g., valid, ready, data).
Detect valid transactions (e.g., when handshake occurs).
Convert raw signals â†’ transaction object.
Send those objects to scoreboard or coverage collector.


â¤ Analogy
Monitor = Security camera ğŸ“¹ â†’ it just observes and records events.

â¤ Example
class my_monitor extends uvm_monitor;
  virtual bus_if vif;
  uvm_analysis_port #(bus_txn) ap;


  task run_phase(uvm_phase phase);
    bus_txn tr;
    forever begin
      @(posedge vif.clk);
      if (vif.valid && vif.ready) begin
        tr = new();
        tr.data = vif.data;
        ap.write(tr); // send to scoreboard
      end
    end
  endtask
endclass

â¡ï¸ It never drives signals â€” only reads them.

